		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
				<p>We consider the question of how well a given distribution can be approximated with probabilistic graphical models. We introduce a new parameter , effective treewidth, that captures the degree of approximability as a tradeoff between the accuracy and the complexity of approximation. We present a simple approach to analyzing achievable tradeoffs that exploits the threshold behavior of monotone graph properties, and provide experimental results that support the approach.</p>
